text: Konamycins A and B and Rubromycins CA1 and CA2, Aromatic Polyketides from the Tunicate-Derived Streptomyces hyaluromycini MB-PO13T Enjuro Harunari, † Biotechnology Research Center and Department of Biotechnology, Toyama Prefectural University, 5180 Kurokawa, Imizu, Toyama 939-0398, Japan ‡ Graduate School of Marine Science and Technology, Tokyo University of Marine Science and Technology, 4-5-7 Konan, Minato-ku, Tokyo 108-8477, Japan *S Supporting Information A wide array of bioactive compounds have been discovered from marine-derived actinomycetes.1 Especially, members of the genus Streptomyces are still recognized as the main screening source for new chemical entities.2 Although many of the actinomycete isolates from marine environments show high similarity of 16S rRNA gene sequence to the terrestrial isolates, their secondary metabolites are often distinctive with unprecedented skeletons and/or unreported combination of known structural units,3 suggesting the speciﬁc evolution of secondary metabolism in marine environments.

In our previous screening of hyaluronidase inhibitors, a new aromatic polyketide, hyaluromycin (5), was found from Streptomyces hyaluromycini MB-PO13T, which was isolated from a tunicate collected in Tokyo Bay, Japan.4,5 During the structure determination of 5, 13C-labeling by adding [1,2-13C2]- acetate into the culture medium was conducted for the complete NMR assignment.4 In the acetate-supplemented culture, production of unknown yellow pigments that were not produced in a nonsupplemented culture was observed. We therefore attempted to isolate and analyze these unknown metabolites, which resulted in the discovery of additional new aromatic polyketides, konamycins A (1) and B (2). Furthermore, in the course of puriﬁcation of 5, two new aromatic polyketides, rubromycins CA1 (3) and CA2 (4), were isolated. We herein report the structure determination and bioactivities of these new compounds (1−4) produced by strain MB-PO13. ABSTRACT: Four new aromatic polyketides, konamycins A (1) and B (2) and rubromycins CA1 (3) and CA2 (4), were the tunicate-derived isolated from the culture extract of Streptomyces hyaluromycini MB-PO13T. Compounds 1 and 2 possess a benzo[b]ﬂuorene aglycon modiﬁed by C-glyco- sylation with L-amicetose. Compounds 3 and 4 are the new congeners of rubromycin in which a naphthoquinone and carboxylated isocoumarin are joined through a spiroketal carbon. The structures of these compounds were determined by extensive analysis of 1D and 2D NMR spectroscopic data. Compound 1 showed radical scavenging activity in DPPH and superoxide quenching assays, and 3 and 4 displayed antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive bacteria. © XXXX American Chemical Society and American Society of Pharmacognosy

Cite This: J. Nat. Prod. XXXX, XXX, XXX−XXX Konamycin A (1) was isolated as an optically active ([α]25 D +124 (c 0.10, MeOH)) yellow gum (6.2 mg from 1 L of culture). The molecular formula of C30H30O13 was established by high- resolution ESITOFMS analysis, which showed a deprotonated molecule [M − H]− at m/z 597.1604. The IR spectrum displayed the absorption bands for hydroxy and carbonyl functionalities at 3353, 1729, and 1645 cm−1. Interpretation of the 1H and 13C NMR spectroscopic data with the aid of the HSQC data allowed the assignment of 30 carbons to seven oxygenated sp2 carbons, seven sp2 carbons, three sp2 methines, one oxygenated sp3 carbon, ﬁve oxygenated sp3 methines, four sp3 methylenes, and three methyl carbons. As 1 was obtained from the culture treated with [1,2-13C2]- acetate, 2D-INADEQUATE experiment was performed to conﬁrm the carbon−carbon connectivity derived from acetate incorporation. With the parameter setting optimized for 1JCC of 45 Hz, 11 correlations were detected for C-1/C-11a, C-2/C-12, C-4/C-4a, C-4b/C-5, C-5a/C-6, C-7/C-8, C-9/C-9a, C-10/C- 10a, C-13/C-14, C-15/C-16, and C-17/C-18 (Figures 2 and S6). Figure 1. COSY, key HMBC, and INADEQUATE correlations of [1,2-13C2]acetate-labeled 1. Figure 2. Conﬁguration analysis of the amicetose moiety of 1. The substructure ﬁrst identiﬁed was a cyclohexenone that was assembled starting from the HMBC correlations from H3-12 to C-1, C-2, and C-3. The H-3 methine was COSY-correlated with H-4, and C-4 was in turn connected to C-4a (Figure 1). H-4 had a long-range coupling to C-11a, which was directly bonded to keto carbonyl C-1, providing a highly oxygenated cyclo- hexenone ring. HMBC correlations were observed from 9-OH to three sp2 carbons (C-8, C-9, C-9a), from H-6 to C-5, C-8, and C-9a, and from H-7 to C-5a and C-9. The sharp singlet resonance for 9-OH was suggestive of its hydrogen bonding to a keto carbonyl oxygen, allowing the placement of C-10 adjacent to C-9a. This spectroscopic evidence established a naphthoqui- none-like substructure consisting of ﬁve acetate units (C-4b/C- 5, C-5a/C-6, C-7/C-8, C-9/C-9a, and C-10/C-10a). Finally, HMBC correlations from H-11 to C-1, C-11a, C-4a, C-4b, C- 10a, and C-10 combined the above-deﬁned substructures to build a benzo[b]ﬂuorene skeleton.

Three more acetate units identiﬁed by INADEQUATE were assigned to comprise a succinyl and an acetyl group. HMBC correlations from H2-14 to C-13 (δ C 170.0), C-15, and C-16 (δ C 173.1) and from H2-15 to C-13, C-14, and C-16 provided a succinyl unit, which was linked to C-3 as an ester by an HMBC correlation from H-3 to C-13. An acetyl group, which was deduced by an HMBC correlation from H3-18 to C-17, was placed at C-4, considering the deshielded chemical shift of H-4 (δ H 4.93). The remaining six carbons were not labeled by 13C- acetate, suggesting that their origin was not the polyketide pathway. Two COSY-deﬁned fragments, H-1′/H2-2′ and H2-3′/ H-4′/H-5′/H3-6′, were joined by HMBC correlations from H- 1′ and H2-2′ to C-3′ and H2-3′ and H-4′ to C-2′. An HMBC correlation from H-1′ to C′-5 closed this six-carbon fragment to provide a tetrahydropyranyl unit bearing methyl and hydroxy substitutions. This cyclic ether portion was connected to the aromatic carbon C-8 on the basis of HMBC correlations from H- 1′ to C-7, C-8, and C-9, completing the planar structure of 1 (Figure 1).

The relative conﬁguration of the tetrahydropyranyl moiety was determined on the basis of 3JHH coupling constants and NOESY correlations. Large coupling constants for H-1′/H-2′b (10.8 Hz) and H-3′b/H-4′ (8.9 Hz) indicated the axial orientation of these protons. NOEs were observed for the proton pairs of H-1′/H-3′b, H-1′/H-5′, H-3′b/H-5′, H-2′b/H- 4′, and H-4′/H3-6′. This spectoscopic information unambigu- ously established the equatorial orientation of 4′-OH and 6′- methyl groups (Figure 2). The absolute conﬁguration of this portion was determined by derivatizing the secondary alcohol at C-4′ to the MPA (α- methoxyphenylacetic acid) ester.6,7 Prior to the MPA esteriﬁcation, 1 was treated with methyl iodide in the presence of DBU (1,8-diazobicyclo[5,4,0]-7-undecene) to give methyl ester 6. The ester 6 was then reacted with one equivalent of (R)- and (S)-MPA to yield the mono-(R)- and (S)-MPA esters (7 and 8), respectively, as the major products. The esters were puriﬁed by reversed-phase HPLC, and the site of esteriﬁcation was conﬁrmed by analysis of COSY and HMBC spectra. In the 1H NMR spectra of 7 and 8, positive Δδ R−S values were observed for H-5′ and H-6′, while negative Δδ R−S values were determined for H2-2′ and H2-3′ (Figure 3). These data allowed assignment DOI: 10.1021/acs.jnatprod.9b00107 J. Nat. Prod. XXXX, XXX, XXX−XXX Journal of Natural Products

of the absolute conﬁguration as 1′R, 4′S, and 5′R, thereby establishing that the deoxysugar moiety was D-amicetose. A large vicinal coupling constant between H-3 and H-4 (9.2 Hz) indicated that substituents at C-3 and C-4 were both equatorial. A NOESY correlation between H-4 and H3-12 established the axial orientation of the H3-12 methyl group at C- 2 (Figure 4). Although several diﬀerent approaches such as Figure 4. Konamycin B (2) was isolated as an optically active ([α]22 D +97 (c 0.05, MeOH)) yellow gum (1.9 mg from 1 L of culture). The molecular formula of C24H24O9 was determined by high- resolution ESITOFMS analysis. The 1H and 13C NMR spectra of 2 were similar to those for 1 except the loss of resonances for succinyl and acetyl groups (Table 1). The mass diﬀerence (142 amu) between 1 and 2 was also supportive of the absence of these two acyl groups in 2, which was consistent with COSY and HMBC correlation data for 2 (Figure S31A). The relative conﬁguration of 2 was determined in the same manner as described for 1. Large coupling constants for H-1′/H2-2′b (11.0 Hz) and H2-3′b/H-4′ (8.8 Hz) conﬁrmed the axial orientation of these protons, thereby establishing the equatorial orientation of the 4′-OH and 6′-methyl groups. A large vicinal coupling constant between H-3 and H-4 (8.8 Hz) indicated that substituents at C-3 and C-4 were both equatorial (Figure S31B). The H3-12 methyl group at C-2 was placed in an axial orientation on the basis of a ROESY correlation between H-4 and H3-12 (Figure S31C). Rubromycin CA1 (3) was obtained as an optically active ([α]22 −33 (c 0.005, DMSO)) red powder (2.1 mg from 1 L of culture). The molecular formula C25H16O12 was deduced from a HRESITOFMS analysis. The presence of hydroxy (2941 cm−1) and carbonyl (1686 cm−1) functional groups was suggested by R−S values for mono-MPA derivatives (7 and 8) of methyl

the IR spectrum. Interpretation of 1H and 13C NMR and HSQC data allowed the assignment of 25 carbons to 11 oxygen-bearing sp2 carbons, three sp2 methines, six sp2 carbons that do not have protons, one oxygenated sp3 carbon, three sp3 methylenes, and one oxygenated methyl group. The UV spectrum of 3 was almost identical with that of a rubromycin/griseorhodin-type aromatic polycyclic system, whereas the 1H NMR spectrum of 3 was closely similar to that of hyaluromycin (5). In addition, an amide proton signal and 1H and 13C resonances for the C5N unit were missing in 3. These observations and the mass diﬀerence of 79 amu between 3 and 5 clariﬁed that the C5N unit was not present in 3, but the carboxy group was substituted at C-7 (Figures 1 and S31D). The absolute conﬁguration of the spiro carbon C-2 (C- 2′) of 3 was determined on the basis of ECD spectroscopic analysis. In its ECD spectrum, two characteristic Cotton eﬀects derived from the interaction of two chromophores connected through a spiro acetal system were observed (Figure 5A). Similar Cotton eﬀect patterns are reported for β-rubromycin, γ- rubromycin, and griseorhodin A,8,9 indicating that the absolute conﬁguration of 3 was identical with that of these known compounds. Therefore, the absolute conﬁguration of the C-2 (C-2′) of 3 was determined to be S.

Rubromycin CA2 (4) was obtained as a red powder (2.6 mg from 1 L of culture). The molecular formula of C25H16O13 was determined on the basis of HRESITOFMS, revealing one more oxygen atom than in 3. The 1H and 13C NMR spectra of 4 were entirely similar to those for 3. Comparison of the 1D and 2D NMR data of 3 and 4 (Table 2) revealed that the H2-3′ methylene of 3 was replaced with a H-3′ methine in 4 and both H-3′ and C-3′ resonances were deshielded signiﬁcantly in 4 compared to 3 from δ C 38.5 to 74.1. In addition, H-3′ was coupled to an exchangeable proton at δ H 6.50. These spectroscopic evidence established that a hydroxy group was substituted at C-3′ in 4 (Figure 6). The absolute conﬁguration of the spiro carbon C-2 was determined to be S by ECD analysis in a similar manner to that described for 3 (Figure 5B).

The absolute conﬁguration of C-3′ was determined by a combination of ROESY and J-based conﬁguration analyses. Two diastereotopic methylene protons (H2-3a and H2-3b) at C-3 could be distinguished by ROE correlation intensity for H2-3b/ H-3′ and H2-3a/3′-OH (Figures 7 and S32). The relative conﬁguration of C-3 and C-4a was determined by J-resolved HMBC analysis (Figures 7 and S33). The large coupling constant (3JCH = 7.1 Hz) of H-3a/C-4a and the small coupling constant (3JCH = 1.8 Hz) of H-3b/C-4a indicated that the conﬁgurations were anti and gauche, respectively. According to these conﬁgurations with the absolute conﬁguration at C-2 (C- 2′), the absolute conﬁguration of C-3′ was determined as S. The biological activities of 1 were evaluated in enzyme- and cell-based assays available in our laboratory, but it was active only in an antioxidative assay. Compound 1 showed 1,1- diphenyl-2-picrylhydrazyl (DPPH) scavenging activity with a 50% scavenging concentration (SC50) value of 21 μM, comparable to Trolox (SC50 9 μM). In addition, 1 was able to quench superoxide generated by superoxide dismutase with an SC50 value of 66 μM, which was comparable to gallic acid (SC50 102 μM). Both 3 and 4 were eﬀective against Gram-positive bacteria including Staphylococcus aureus and Mycobacterium smegmatis (Table 3). Compound 4 was also active against ﬁlamentous fungi. Each compound possesses unique, new structural features, suggesting that marine actino- mycetes are still a promising source of new secondary metabolites. Konamycins A (1) and B (2) are new members of the benzo[b]ﬂuorene antibiotics, which have been exclusively found from actinomycetes (Figure 8).10−16 Konamycin is the ﬁrst example of the benzo[b]ﬂuorene that is modiﬁed with a C- glycoside and succinic acid. Amicetose is not very rare in actinomycete metabolites, but its C-glycoside is only known for aquayamycin-type angucyclines.17−20 Utilization of succinic acid as a building block in natural products is limited to secondary metabolites of Streptomyces such as baﬁlomycins C1 and C2,21 decilorubicin,22 reveromycin,23 and antibiotic 301.24 Rubromycins CA1 (3) and CA2 (4) possess a carboxyl terminus that all other rubromycins do not have. Benzo[b]ﬂuorenes found from actinomycetes. Microorganism. Strain MB-PO13 was isolated from a tunicate (Molgula manhattensis) collected in Tokyo Bay, Japan. This strain is the type strain of Streptomyces hyaluromycini.5

Fermentation and Isolation. Strain MB-PO13 growing on a yeast-starch agar medium consisting of soluble starch (Wako Pure Chemical Industries, Ltd.) 1.0%, yeast extract (Difco Laboratories) 0.2%, and agar 1.5% (pH 7.2) was inoculated into 500 mL K-1 ﬂasks (custom-ordered cylindrical ﬂasks) each containing 100 mL of the V-22 seed medium consisting of soluble starch 1.0%, glucose 0.5%, NZ-case (Wako Pure Chemical Industries, Ltd.) 0.3%, yeast extract 0.2%, ·7H2O Tryptone (Difco Laboratories) 0.5%, K2HPO4 0.1%, MgSO4 0.05%, and CaCO3 0.3% (pH 7.0). The ﬂasks were placed on a rotary shaker (200 rpm) at 30 °C for 4 days. Then, the seed culture (3 mL) was transferred into 500 mL K-1 ﬂasks each containing 100 mL of the A-3M production medium consisting of soluble starch 2.0%, glycerol 2.0%, glucose 0.5%, Pharmamedia (Trader’s Protein) 1.5%, yeast extract 0.3%, and Diaion HP-20 resin (Mitsubishi Chemical Co.) 1%. The pH of the medium was adjusted to 7.0 before sterilization. The 10 inoculated ﬂasks were placed on a rotary shaker (200 rpm) at 30 °C for 7 days.

After incubation, 100 mL of EtOAc was added to each ﬂask, and the ﬂasks were allowed to shake for 1 h. The mixture was centrifuged at 6000 rpm for 10 min, and the organic layer was separated from the aqueous layer containing the mycelium. Then, the aqueous layer (1 L) was extracted with 1 L of 1-butanol in the same manner as described above. The butanol layer was evaporated to give 81.3 mg of extract from 1 L of culture. This extract was subjected to reversed-phase ODS column chromatography with a gradient of MeCN/0.1% HCO2H solution (2:8, 3:7, 4:6, 5:5, 6:4, 7:3, and 8:2 v/v). The fraction eluted with 60% MeCN was evaporated, and the remaining aqueous layer was extracted twice with BuOH and concentrated to give a yellow solid (21.6 mg). The ﬁnal puriﬁcation was achieved by preparative HPLC using a gradient conditions of MeCN/0.1% HCO2H solution (MeCN concentration: 15−85% over 0−30 min) at 4 mL/min, yielding konamycin A (1, 12.6 mg) and konamycin B (2, 1.9 mg) with a retention time of 22.2 and 18.5 min, respectively. Evaporation of the EtOAc extract of the culture broth gave 740 mg of EtOAc extract. This extract was subjected to reversed-phase ODS column chromatography with a gradient of MeCN/0.1% HCO2H solution (2:8, 3:7, 4:6, 5:5, 6:4, 7:3, and 8:2 v/v). The fractions 4 and 5 were combined and evaporated, and the remaining aqueous solution was extracted with EtOAc. The organic layer was then concentrated to give a red solid (13.8 mg). Preparation of 1 Labeled by [1,2-13C2]Acetate. [1,2-13C2]- Acetate-labeled 1 was prepared by culturing the producing strain in a liquid medium containing sodium [1,2-13C2]acetate. The inoculation, cultivation, extraction, and puriﬁcation were conducted in the same manner as described above. Addition of sodium [1,2-13C2]acetate was started at 48 h after inoculation and periodically carried out four times every 24 h. After further incubation for 24 h, the culture broth was extracted with 1-BuOH. After supplementing with sodium [1,2-13C2]- acetate (total 800 mg; 20 mg × 10 ﬂasks × 4 days), 12.6 mg of 13C2- labeled 1 was obtained from 1 L of culture.

Methylation of 1. DBU (8 μL, 0.054 μmol) and CH3I (80 μL, 1.286 μmol) were added to a stirred solution of 1 (4.0 mg, 0.166 μmol) in acetone/MeCN (100 μL each). After heating at 50 °C for 1 h, the reaction mixture was diluted with H2O and 1-BuOH (100 μL each), and the organic layer was separated and evaporated in vacuo. The residue was puriﬁed by preparative HPLC using a linear gradient of MeCN/0.1% HCO2H solution (MeCN concentration: 15−85% for 0− 30 min) at 4 mL/min to give a methyl ester of konamycin A (6, 2.9 mg, 73% yield, tR 25.6 min): yellow gum; HRESITOFMS m/z 611.1758 [M − H]− (calcd for C31H30O13, 611.1759).

Biological Assays. Antimicrobial assay was carried out against Escherichia coli NIH-JC2, Kocuria rhizophila ATCC 9341 (Micrococcus luteus ATCC 9341), Bacillus subtilis PCI 219, Bacillus cereus NBRC 15305, Staphylococcus aureus IFO 12732, Enterococcus faecalis NBRC 100480, Mycobacterium smegmatis NBRC 3207, Candida albicans NBRC 1594, and Kluyveromyces f ragilis ATCC 8635. Mueller Hinton broth (DIFCO) was used for bacteria, and yeast nitrogen base (DIFCO) supplemented with 2% glucose was used for C. albicans and K. f ragilis. Test microorganisms were inoculated into a 32 mL test tube containing 8 mL of the liquid medium. After incubation on a reciprocal shaker for 20 h at 30 °C, the cells were collected by centrifugation (3000 rpm, 5 min) and the cell suspension (1 × 105 cells/mL) was prepared in saline. Then, the liquid medium (135 μL), the cell suspension (15 μL), and the sample solution in DMSO (0.5 to 1 μL) were added into the wells of a 96-well culture plate, and the plate was agitated gently to mix the solution. After incubation for 20 h at 37 °C (E. coli) or 30 °C (M. luteus, C. albicans), the absorbance at 650 nm was measured using a microplate reader. Superoxide dismutase activity was determined by the SOD assay kit WST (Dojindo Molecular Technologies, Inc.). DPPH radical scavenging activity was determined by a DPPH antioxidant assay kit (Dojindo Molecular Technologies, Inc.).
